sult of over five years of close collaboration among an international group of leading typologists within the EUROTYP program, this volume is about the morphology and syntax of the noun phrase. Particular attention is being paid to nominal inflectional categories and inflectional systems and to the syntax of determination, modification, and conjunction. Its areal focus, like that of other EUROTYP volumes, is on the languages of Europe; but in order to appreciate what is peculiarly European about their noun phrases, a more comprehensive and genuinely typological view is being taken at the full range of cross-linguistic variation within this structural domain. There has been no shortage lately of contributions to the theory of noun phrase structure; the present volume is, however, unique in the extent to which its theorizing is empirically grounded.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aTypology (Linguistics). 4aNominalgruppe. 4aSyntax. 4aTypologie (Sprache). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aCorbett, Greville G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGil, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurford, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKibrik, Aleksandr E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoptjevskaja-Tamm, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoravcsik, Edith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlank, Frans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlank, Frans, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStassen, Leon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part o